I guarantee you they don't
sell those tickets.

268
00:15:01,410 --> 00:15:04,743
Hey, look. There's Bobby Leighton's
father-in-law. Mr. Reichman.

269
00:15:04,913 --> 00:15:06,906
George and I were just talking
about him.

270
00:15:07,458 --> 00:15:09,166
He threw George out of the wedding.

271
00:15:09,543 --> 00:15:11,832
Oh, yeah, when George
made that bad toast.

272
00:15:12,004 --> 00:15:15,337
- You remember the curse toast?
- Oh, yeah. The curse toast.

273
00:15:15,549 --> 00:15:16,877
Can you believe that message?

274
00:15:17,051 --> 00:15:19,257
I gotta spend my life looking
over my shoulder.

275
00:15:19,428 --> 00:15:21,302
Me too.

276
00:15:22,431 --> 00:15:25,432
Crazy Joe Davola.

277
00:15:26,351 --> 00:15:28,925
- How do you know his name?
- Why wouldn't I know his name?

278
00:15:29,354 --> 00:15:32,024
- I never told you his name.
- I never told you his name.

279
00:15:32,858 --> 00:15:35,064
- Who are we talking about here?
- Joe Davola.

280
00:15:35,235 --> 00:15:37,561
Right, Joe Davola.

281
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:39,858
How do you know his name?

282
00:15:40,449 --> 00:15:44,778
I've been out with him three times.
I should know the man's name.

283
00:15:45,454 --> 00:15:48,371
- Oh, my God! It's Joe Davola?
- He's stalking you?

284
00:15:48,540 --> 00:15:50,699
- Are you kidding me?
- You're dating the madman...

285
00:15:50,876 --> 00:15:53,793
- ...who's trying to kill me?
- Why didn't you tell me his name?

286
00:15:53,962 --> 00:15:56,085
Last night he accused me
of seeing someone else.

287
00:15:56,256 --> 00:15:58,545
- He said, "Tell me his name!"
- He said that?

288
00:15:58,717 --> 00:16:00,793
If he sees us, can you imagine
what he'll do?

289
00:16:00,969 --> 00:16:03,377
If he thinks I ruined his NBC deal
and stole his girl!

290
00:16:03,555 --> 00:16:06,473
- That will be a kibosh for sure.
- What about me?

291
00:16:06,642 --> 00:16:08,266
Excuse me.

292
00:16:08,894 --> 00:16:11,302
Come on. This is Pavarotti.

293
00:16:11,688 --> 00:16:14,144
Three hundred dollars.
That's a lot of money.

294
00:16:14,316 --> 00:16:17,352
Steven Holtzman did a production
in Tunis last year.

295
00:16:17,528 --> 00:16:21,110
From what I understand,
the Muslims really took to it.

296
00:16:21,448 --> 00:16:25,316
I'll tell you what. You seem like a
nice guy. Let's stop jerking around.

297
00:16:25,786 --> 00:16:29,997
Give me $250. I got people waiting
for me. I gotta get the hell out of here.

298
00:16:30,290 --> 00:16:33,161
Scalping. I told them
to put on extra security.

299
00:16:33,335 --> 00:16:34,746
Excuse me.

300
00:16:35,087 --> 00:16:37,756
Pop, would you buzz off?
I got something cooking here.

301
00:16:37,923 --> 00:16:40,129
- Costanza?
- Mr. Reichman?

302
00:16:40,300 --> 00:16:42,340
Still a sewer-mouth.
Give me those tickets.

303
00:16:42,511 --> 00:16:48,098
Harold, don't. Harold, be careful
of your hair transplant!

304
00:16:48,267 --> 00:16:50,758
Anything is welcome.
I accept change.

305
00:16:50,936 --> 00:16:53,771
I don't have anything.
I gave it to that guy.

306
00:16:55,691 --> 00:16:58,016
You know, you could just say no.

307
00:16:58,193 --> 00:16:59,652
You don't have to humiliate me.

308
00:16:59,820 --> 00:17:03,189
I may be dressed as a clown,
but I am a person.

309
00:17:03,365 --> 00:17:05,856
- The guy took-
- I don't need people like you...

310
00:17:06,034 --> 00:17:07,612
...looking down their noses at me.

311
00:17:07,786 --> 00:17:11,784
I am just a street performer
trying to make enough to get by.

312
00:17:11,957 --> 00:17:14,413
Doctor. Is there a doctor anywhere?

313
00:17:14,585 --> 00:17:16,127
We need a doctor!

314
00:17:16,295 --> 00:17:19,664
What are you, showing off
for your girlfriend here, is that it?

315
00:17:19,840 --> 00:17:23,885
I'm not his girlfriend. We dated
for a while but things didn't work out.

316
00:17:24,219 --> 00:17:27,137
You people make me sick.

317
00:17:30,559 --> 00:17:33,560
That is one angry clown.

318
00:17:33,729 --> 00:17:35,556
The hardest part
about being a clown...

319
00:17:35,731 --> 00:17:39,479
...it seems to me, would be that you're
constantly referred to as a clown.

320
00:17:39,651 --> 00:17:42,059
"Who is that clown?
I'm not working with that clown.

321
00:17:42,237 --> 00:17:43,696
Did you hire that clown?

322
00:17:43,864 --> 00:17:45,239
The guy's a clown."

323
00:17:45,449 --> 00:17:47,323
How do you even start into
being a clown?

324
00:17:47,492 --> 00:17:49,236
How do you know you
wanna be a clown?

325
00:17:49,411 --> 00:17:52,198
I guess you just get to a point
where your pants look so bad...

326
00:17:52,831 --> 00:17:54,788
...it's actually easier
to become a clown...

327
00:17:54,958 --> 00:17:57,081
...than having the proper alterations
done.

328
00:17:57,419 --> 00:18:01,251
If you think about it, a clown,
if there isn't a circus around them...

329
00:18:01,423 --> 00:18:03,879
...is really just a very annoying person.

330
00:18:04,051 --> 00:18:07,420
I mean, you're in the back seat
of this guy's Volkswagen-

331
00:18:07,596 --> 00:18:10,881
"What, you're picking somebody
else up? Oh, man."

332
00:18:11,308 --> 00:18:14,344
<i>I got one. Who needs one?
Pagliacci. Pagliacci.</i>

333
00:18:14,770 --> 00:18:17,012
<i>The tragic clown. Pagliacci...</i>

334
00:18:21,568 --> 00:18:23,312
What did you say?

335
00:18:24,321 --> 00:18:25,981
What, are you a cop?

336
00:18:26,990 --> 00:18:28,734
No. I'm a clown.

337
00:18:30,410 --> 00:18:32,368
Man, you look familiar.

338
00:18:33,580 --> 00:18:35,039
You ever been to the circus?

339
00:18:35,707 --> 00:18:38,079
- Well, when I was a kid.
- Did you like it?

340
00:18:38,252 --> 00:18:40,707
Well, it was fun.

341
00:18:41,380 --> 00:18:43,953
Was kind of scared of the clowns.

342
00:18:45,384 --> 00:18:47,756
Are you still scared of clowns?

343
00:18:49,054 --> 00:18:50,632
Yeah.

344
00:18:53,267 --> 00:18:54,642
We're gonna miss the overture.

345
00:18:54,810 --> 00:19:01,144
<i>Overture, curtains, lights
This is it, we'll hit the heights</i>

346
00:19:01,316 --> 00:19:07,485
<i>And, oh, what heights we'll hit
On with the show, this is it</i>

347
00:19:11,326 --> 00:19:13,948
You know, it is so sad.

348
00:19:14,121 --> 00:19:17,157
All your knowledge of high culture
comes from Bugs Bunny cartoons.

349
00:19:19,334 --> 00:19:22,419
Oh, there's that clown again.
What does he want from me?

350
00:19:22,713 --> 00:19:24,919
Look, I'm serious.
I don't have the quarter.

351
00:19:25,090 --> 00:19:27,663
- That guy took it.
- I don't want any money.

352
00:19:29,511 --> 00:19:31,587
I smell cherry.

353
00:19:34,016 --> 00:19:36,471
- It's Binaca.
- Binaca?

354
00:19:41,523 --> 00:19:42,768
Go! Go!

355
00:19:43,025 --> 00:19:46,440
- All right, what did we say, 275?
- Two-fifty.

356
00:19:47,070 --> 00:19:50,439
- Two-fifty? Are you sure?
- Yeah, yeah, I'm sure.

357
00:19:50,907 --> 00:19:53,280
- All right. All right, 250.
- George!

358
00:19:53,910 --> 00:19:55,868
- Susan.
- I don't believe it.

359
00:19:56,038 --> 00:19:58,114
I'm so glad I caught you.

360
00:19:58,457 --> 00:20:01,030
What are you doing here?
You were going to the airport.

361
00:20:01,209 --> 00:20:03,368
Some plane problems.
They landed in Philadelphia.

362
00:20:03,545 --> 00:20:06,380
So what? They don't have another
plane? She couldn't take a bus?

363
00:20:06,548 --> 00:20:08,956
She's coming in tomorrow.
But I made it.

364
00:20:09,134 --> 00:20:11,257
Yeah. How about that? You made it.

365
00:20:11,428 --> 00:20:14,714
I'm so excited. Now we get to see
the opera together.

366
00:20:14,890 --> 00:20:18,389
We get to go to the opera-
Get out of here- Together.

367
00:20:18,560 --> 00:20:21,051
- Who's that?
- That's, that's Harry Fong.

368
00:20:21,229 --> 00:20:23,851
He's a very good friend of mine.
He's a big opera buff.

369
00:20:24,024 --> 00:20:26,693
Enjoy the show there, Harry!

370
00:20:26,902 --> 00:20:29,819
- Come on. Let's go.
- You know what?

371
00:20:29,988 --> 00:20:32,479
- Come on. You gotta let us in.
- Not without tickets.

372
00:20:32,657 --> 00:20:34,531
We have tickets. Just not with us.

373
00:20:34,701 --> 00:20:37,572
Well, that's a problem. Excuse me.

374
00:20:38,205 --> 00:20:40,660
You don't understand.
Someone's after us, a crazy clown.

375
00:20:40,832 --> 00:20:43,750
- He's trying to kill us!
- A crazy clown is after you?

376
00:20:43,919 --> 00:20:46,326
Oh, that's rich.

377
00:20:46,505 --> 00:20:48,628
Clear the way so people
with tickets can pass.

378
00:20:48,799 --> 00:20:50,672
- We're with him.
- Are you guys ready?

379
00:20:50,842 --> 00:20:52,420
- Yes. Yes.
- Have you seen George?

380
00:20:52,594 --> 00:20:55,050
- We thought he was with you.
- Come on. He's on his own.

381
00:20:55,222 --> 00:20:56,680
Here.

382
00:20:58,016 --> 00:20:59,925
Here I come.

383
00:21:01,853 --> 00:21:04,309
- These are great seats, huh?
- Yeah.

384
00:21:05,148 --> 00:21:08,897
Boy, some cast, huh?
Pavarotti, Eva Marton.

385
00:21:09,069 --> 00:21:11,275
Eva Marton. I've heard of her.

386
00:21:11,446 --> 00:21:15,111
- Who's she playing?
- She's playing Pagliacci's wife, Nedda.

387
00:21:15,283 --> 00:21:17,691
- Nedda?
- Yeah.

388
00:21:17,911 --> 00:21:19,109
Oh, my God.

389
00:21:19,287 --> 00:21:22,656
Excuse me. Excuse me.

390
00:21:22,833 --> 00:21:24,113
Excuse me.

391
00:21:24,292 --> 00:21:26,119
Excuse me.

392
00:21:36,596 --> 00:21:38,636
Susan, what are you doing here?

393
00:21:38,807 --> 00:21:40,930
- My friend's flight couldn't make it.
- Hi.

394
00:21:41,101 --> 00:21:43,853
- Where's George?
- I got his ticket.

395
00:21:44,020 --> 00:21:46,772
He decided not to come.
He said he was uncomfortable.

396
00:21:46,940 --> 00:21:48,351
Uncomfortable?

397
00:21:48,525 --> 00:21:50,399
How do you think I feel?

398
00:21:51,653 --> 00:21:55,104
- How much did you pay for that ticket?
- One-seventy-five.

399
00:21:57,659 --> 00:21:59,984
Kramer, who did you sell
your ticket to?

400
00:22:00,162 --> 00:22:03,162
Some nut in a clown suit.

401
00:22:10,297 --> 00:22:13,416
I had some friends drag me
to an opera recently.

402
00:22:13,592 --> 00:22:15,631
They've all got those little
opera glasses.

403
00:22:15,802 --> 00:22:19,670
Do you really need binoculars?
How big do these people have to get...

404
00:22:20,015 --> 00:22:21,213
...before you can spot them?

405
00:22:21,391 --> 00:22:26,634
These opera kids, they're going
250, 280, 325.

406
00:22:26,813 --> 00:22:28,853
